what's the advantage of returning an std::unique_ptr<FileWriter> in this situation ?

1000
Tue Apr 21 17:12:23 2015 +0000
Author: Elliott Hughes <1003224@85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889>
Parent: 70f6329f_0e1d2b66
UUID: d01a7eb3_b2a55581
Bytes: 670
(a) it's what all the cool kids are doing, but (b) it forces callers to take ownership. yes, the fact that a function is returning a raw pointer is a strong clue, but returning a std::unique_ptr means the compiler won't let you ignore that. it goes from being a human-readable hint to a compiler-enforceable requirement.

are you likely to screw up here, where everything's in a single file? probably not. but my feeling is we probably want to get into the habit of this quickly so it becomes the default idiom.

google3 is already moving in that direction: https://google-styleguide.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/cppguide.html#Ownership_and_Smart_Pointers (under "Decision")

